The following is a Python function that determines whether a number is prime or not:

def is_prime(number):
    if number <= 1:
        return False
    for i in range(2, int(number ** 0.5) + 1):
        if number % i == 0:
            return False
    return True

This function takes an integer number as an argument and returns True if the number is prime and False otherwise. The for loop checks whether the number is divisible by any number except 1 and itself.

To generate a table of contents in a LATEX document, you can use the package "tocbibind". Here is an example code:

\begin{code}
\begin{filecontents*}{mybib.bib}
@book{knuth1992literate,
  author = {Knuth, Donald E.},
  title = {The Literate Programmer},
  publisher = {Addison-Wesley},
  year = {1992},
}
@article{stegun1952table,
  author = {Stegun, Carl B.},
  title = {Table of Contents},
  journal = {Society for Industrial and Applied Mathematics},
  volume = {1},
  pages = {1--2},
}
\end{filecontents*}

\documentclass[12pt,a4paper,sans,english]{book}
\usepackage[T1]{fontenc}
\usepackage{tocbibind}
\bibliographystyle{unsrt}
\usepackage{lipsum}

\begin{document}

\tableofcontents
\listofsymbols
\input{mybib}
\lipsum[1-3]
\printbibliography

\end{document}
\end{code}

In this example, the package "tocbibind" is used to generate a table of contents, and the file "mybib.bib" contains two entries: one is the book "The Literate Programmer" by Donald E. Knuth and the other is an article "Table of Contents" by Carl B. Stegun.

The command \tableofcontents generates the table of contents, while \listofsymbols prints a list of symbols used in the document. \input{mybib} includes the bibfile "mybib.bib" into the document, which contains the two entries. Finally, \printbibliography prints the bibliography at the end of the document.

This is just a basic example of how to generate a table of contents in a LATEX document. You can customize it to fit your needs by changing the style of the table of contents, the location of the bibliography, etc.

